/-
We formalized the definition of the diagonal Ramsey number $R(k)$ and proved the lower bound $R(k) > (\sqrt{2})^k$ for $k \ge 3$.
The proof uses the probabilistic method: we show that the expected number of monochromatic $k$-cliques in a random graph on $n = \lfloor 2^{k/2} \rfloor$ vertices is less than 1.
This implies the existence of a graph with no monochromatic $k$-cliques, and thus $R(k) > n$.
The main theorem is `diagonalRamsey_gt_sqrt2_pow_k`.
We assumed the finiteness of Ramsey numbers (`∃ M, IsRamsey k M`) as a hypothesis for the main theorem, as proving Ramsey's theorem itself was outside the scope of the lower bound proof.
